div.p:
                    Sowing. Being thus provided with good seede, sow it as they do in Italy or France. 
The Italians sow it in cases and shallow tubes in the full moon of August;

It comes speedily up, and will be very strong before Winter: when the Frosts come remove them into your Cellar, or Garden-house, till the Spring, and that the Frosts are gone, and then transplant them into good mould; thus you shall have white, very fair heads, and well conditioned before the great heats of Sommer surprize them.

                    Time. 
                    Thyme is both sown and planted; 
One Thyme tuft wil afford many slips, which you may set with the setting-stick, as you doe all sorts of cuttings.
